0alarmed%20that%20some%20of%20her%20colleagues%2C%20especially%20some%20of%20the%20court's%20conservatives%2C%20seemed%20more%20afraid%20of%20limiting%20presidential%20immunity%20the%20court%20would%20neuter%20by%20the%20presidency%20by%20forcing%20future%20leaders%20to%20question%20if%20a%20political%20rival%20would%20try%20to%20prosecute%20them%20after%20they%20left%20office.%20%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EInstead%2C%20Jackson%20said%20there%20should%20be%20at%20least%20equal%20consideration%20given%20to%20the%20possibility%20that%20by%20granting%20sweeping%20immunity%2C%20the%20nation's%20highest%20court%20would%20give%20a%20green%20light%20to%20presidential%20criminality%20if%20a%20future%20president%20could%20even%20tangentially%20tie%20criminal%20actions%20to%20carrying%20out%20the%20job%20of%20leading%20the%20nation.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BPresidents%20from%20the%20beginning%20of%20time%20have%20understood%20that%20that's%20a%20possibility%2C%26quot%3B%20Jackson%20said%20later%20of%20how%20past%20leaders%20understood%20they%20could%20be%20prosecuted%20after%20leaving%20office.%20%26quot%3BThat%20might%20be%20what%20has%20kept%20this%20office%20from%20turning%20into%20the%20kind%20of%20crime%20center%20that%20I'm%20envisioning.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EJackson%20repeatedly%20underlined%20her%20points%20when%20questioning%20Sauer%2C%20underlining%20how%20far%20future%20presidents%20could%20push%20the%20envelope.%20She%20seemed%20particularly%20drawn%20to%20a%20brief%20filed%20by%20Georgetown%20Law%20School%20professor%20Martin%20Lederman%20that%20outlined%20how%20presidents%20with%20immunity%20could%20commit%20perjury%2C%20destroy%20or%20conceal%20documents%2C%20or%20bribe%20other%20public%20officials.%20%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EJackson's%20concerns%20are%20based%20on%20another%20element%20of%20Trump's%20arguments%2C%20which%20propose%20that%20a%20president%20could%20not%20be%20charged%20with%20a%20crime%20unless%20the%20law%20they%20are%20accused%20of%20violating%20specifical